    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-01-19T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-01-19T00:00:00-05:00" n="83" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d83">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">No. 57.</note>
                <head>
                    <persName type="from">Mr. Campbell</persName> to <persName type="to">the Secretary of State</persName>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-01-19">
                            <hi rend="italic">January</hi> 19, 1872.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: * * * * * * *</p>
                <p>I can say from my own knowledge that after the discovery of gold on
                            Fraser River in 1858, the canal de Haro was the *ordinary channel of
                            communication between Victoria and British Columbia, and doubtless now
                            is, and ever will be.<seg type="margin">[71]</seg>
                    <seg type="margin">The
                                Haro channel the usual channel.</seg>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>ARCHIBALD CAMPBELL, <hi rend="italic">Late United States
                                    Boundary Commissioner.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
